        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>owld M[iste]r Wythipolls saying to his sonnes:</marginalia_text>
                    <!--JG: Unsure which Withipoll Harvey means. His notebook includes the names of Daniel and Bartholomew-->
                    <!--KS: Daniel and Bartholomew Wythipoll were Harvey's contemporaries, so 'owld Mr Wythipoll' could be their father, the politician Edmund?-->
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>Scribit[u]r in a[e]dibus, qui non ualet Equis, ualet pedibus.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>It is written in the house: who is not strong by horse, is strong by foot.</translation> 
            <!--JG: Chris, please check. Seems as there is a pun, but hard to render it-->
            <!-- CG: I think 'aedibus' might mean something more like 'temples,' but it's unclear. I'm also wondering  if
            there's another way of translating 'valet' to be more like 'has value' or 'is effective' since the text is talking about
            using footsoldiers to carry stuff, rather than horses. -->
            <!--JG: Hmm, could be. Perhaps something like: he who does not prevail on horse, prevails on foot-->
